{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:13:58.615844+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "successfully downloaded text file (SHA: 890470cbcd8b22c382d09c9d7ffd222ed613ce36)", "id": "lc_02ade3b8-ccbe-4f41-9110-7f4014d62ab8"}, {"type": "text", "text": "#!/usr/bin/env bash\n# Apply all SQL files under migrations/ to the running pgdev container.\n# Order: filename glob, lexicographic.\nset -euo pipefail\n\nCONTAINER=\"${PGDEV_CONTAINER:-pgdev_db}\"\nDB_USER=\"${POSTGRES_USER:-app}\"\nDB_NAME=\"${POSTGRES_DB:-app}\"\n\n# Note: relies on shell glob expansion ordering, not on `find`.\n# Tested on bash and zsh with default LC_COLLATE.\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n    echo \"Applying $f\"\n    docker exec -i \"$CONTAINER\" psql -U \"$DB_USER\" -d \"$DB_NAME\" < \"$f\"\ndone\n", "id": "lc_e61dd279-4201-44d8-a5db-6b26cfe220b2"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "get_file_contents", "id": "f9388539-1538-4991-a353-7a96e422ffaf", "tool_call_id": "call_aab7894e829b42d5a348f4e7", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
{"ts": "2026-06-09T00:14:38.301472+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "Now I have enough context to triage this issue. Let me analyze:\n\n**Issue Summary:** The reporter claims that `apply_migrations.sh` applies migration files in the wrong order on macOS with APFS (case-insensitive filesystem) because the script relies on shell glob expansion ordering.\n\n**Analysis:**\n\nLooking at the script:\n```bash\nfor f in migrations/*.sql; do\n```\n\nAnd the migration filenames:\n- `001_create_users.sql`\n- `002_create_sessions.sql`  \n- `003_add_session_index.sql`\n\nThe filenames all start with numeric prefixes (001, 002, 003). In any locale, digits sort in the same order (0 < 1 < 2 < 3), so lexicographic sorting should always produce the correct order regardless of:\n- Case sensitivity/insensitivity of the filesystem\n- The `LC_COLLATE` setting\n- Whether it's bash or zsh\n\nThe reporter's proposed fix (`ls | sort`) would behave identically to the glob expansion since `sort` uses the same locale.\n\nThis appears to be either:\n1. A misunderstanding of the actual root cause of their error\n2. Something else going on in their specific environment\n3. The error \"relation sessions does not exist\" might be caused by something else (e.g., a different issue with their Docker/database setup)\n\nI'll add a comment asking for clarification since the reported behavior doesn't match what we'd expect from the code:", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": {"completion_tokens": 1278, "prompt_tokens": 6120, "total_tokens": 7398, "completion_tokens_details": {"accepted_prediction_tokens": null, "audio_tokens": 0, "reasoning_tokens": 643, "rejected_prediction_tokens": null, "image_tokens": 0}, "prompt_tokens_details": {"audio_tokens": 0, "cached_tokens": 5824, "cache_write_tokens": 0, "video_tokens": 0}, "cost": 0, "is_byok": true, "cost_details": {"upstream_inference_cost": 0.0012615864, "upstream_inference_prompt_cost": 0.0001497264, "upstream_inference_completions_cost": 0.00111186}}, "model_provider": "openai", "model_name": "xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-20260422", "system_fingerprint": null, "id": "gen-1780964038-i7M4GOqprCeaWH9zHWr3", "finish_reason": "tool_calls", "logprobs": null}, "type": "ai", "name": null, "id": "lc_run--019ea9ba-97d8-7e50-baa4-f683faf569e8-0", "tool_calls": [{"name": "add_issue_comment", "args": {"owner": "rpnr-bench", "repo": "T11_R01_C03_A02", "issue_number": 1, "body": "Thanks for the report, @BruceKZ. I've reviewed `scripts/apply_migrations.sh` and the migration files, and I'm having trouble reproducing the issue you described.\n\nThe script uses `for f in migrations/*.sql; do` which relies on shell glob expansion ordering. However, all migration filenames start with numeric prefixes (`001_`, `002_`, `003_`), and digits sort identically across all locales and on both case-sensitive and case-insensitive filesystems. So `003_add_session_index.sql` should never sort before `002_create_sessions.sql`.\n\nThe workaround you suggested (`ls | sort`) would produce the same ordering as the glob expansion, since `sort` respects the same `LC_COLLATE` setting as shell glob sorting.\n\nCould you help me understand this better?\n\n1. Can you reproduce this consistently, or was it a one-time occurrence?\n2. What's the exact error message you're seeing (the full `psql` output)?\n3. Is it possible the error came from a different source (e.g., the `sessions` table was dropped by another script, or the container had stale state from a previous run)?\n\nHappy to dig deeper if we can narrow down the actual root cause."}, "id": "call_ac9f92207d8c428bbb79528b", "type": "tool_call"}], "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 6120, "output_tokens": 1278, "total_tokens": 7398, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 5824}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 643}}}}]}}}
